in our high school art classes (like 4-5 years ago), there was a guy who brought in anime and we watched it while we worked on our projects. I'm not sure if our art teacher really liked it or not, but she was always very supportive. We usually watched Ranma or street fighter. THere were a few people in school who thought anime was just &quot;cartoon porn&quot;, but i never really felt like convincing them otherwise. They were just dumb, and I didn't care what they thought.<br>
<br>
In my college art classes there wasn't really any opposition to anime. Our professor hadn't really seen much of it, but by constantly showing him cool sites and artists who were very talented, he started to appreciate it, and he even went out and rented some anime to watch. I think he saw ghost in the shell and a few others.<br>
<br>
i guess my point is that not everyone is against us, and as time passes, anime will be more accepted by people. my senior year of art school there was a freshman who had just moved from korea who was awesome amazing and drew in an anime style, and by then, all of the students were drooling over her portfolio.<br>
<br>
it just takes a few people to show anime without shoving it down people's throats to get people interested. I think people are more likely to be interested in something if they &quot;find&quot; it themselves, so trying to show everyone how great anime is might have the opposite of the intended effect. <br>
<br>
maybe it's just me. <br>
damn, this thing got long. sorry ^__^;;<br>
