<br>
I used to have a really narrow-minded teacher in my secondary school, a stuffy old guy in my college and my boy friend used to be opposed to my art, but the most important thing I have learned is that you should never, never let it get to you, because you are doing something you enjoy. The teachers are irrelevant now, and Cid is beginning to see sense, and I am still doing my art, so all is well.<br>
<br>
I know the pain of having art criticised or torn up, especially if it took ages, and the only thing I can say is  that if they are too ignorant to let you enjoy art and try to cram you into a style you are not happy with, then they (art teachers especially) will see a drastic slump in your performance.<br>
<br>
Let the art breathe, start an Anime/Manga group in your area, and offer each other support and critiques.<br>
<br>
Remember:<br>
   A person is smart,<br>
   People are stupid <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pahsia>Pa Hsia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(10/31/02 5:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1988.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_thumbsup.gif" align=absmiddle>  Don't attack Anime</span><hr size=1> I can completely relate to what you're saying, and it was much harder for me, being ripped for being a Manga artist and being gay, but persevere.<br>
